Andala is a middle eastern coffee and falafel place with friendly service, close to Central station. I’ve been to Andala a few times on different occasions. Very authentic and cozy cafe with an extensive loose leaf tea menu - a rarity for the Boston area. However, I deduct two stars for a ruined experience today. First, it was a nice sunny day but the waiters refused to let us to the outdoor patio with a stroller, claiming that “outdoor seating is reserved for clients with hookah”. Needless to say nobody had hookah there, so clearly demonstrated that “not welcome here with the kids attitude”. Then we climbed up the stairs with a stroller, sat at the table (I still wanted their majestic tea), but nobody served us in 20 minutes and we left. Bottom line: it’s still a good place to go without kids, the food is great, but the service is slow and has has that strong anti-family attitude I never saw in the US before.

If it's a nice day in Central Square and you like hookah, Andala Coffee House is a great place to stop and get a hookah outdoors.  Friendly service, free self-serve water, and a great selection of teas and other beverages.  They don't serve alcohol though and the patio gets full so count yourself lucky if you can even get a spot.  If you do though, the setting sun should light you up beautifully so you might not even need a filter.

Andala is one of my favorite spots in Cambridge.  A charming gem, completely unique.  Cozy in the winter,  sparkling with light and air inside with vine covered sidewalk patio in the summer. The coffee shop was sort of hidden at the corner of a Main Street off Central Square. I went inside on a Sunday afternoon around 2:30Pmish, the place was quite packed. I was intrigued by its various cultural extravagant decor and Palestinian flags. The vibe was very young and energizing. I ordered a latte since the staff didn’t really know what a “flat white” was when I ordered. I had to say the coffee was quite mediocre, mostly tasted like foamed milk, maybe that’s what it should be like since in Italy ordering latte will get you a milk served. The one shot of coffee didn’t offer much taste at all, maybe try two expresso shots next time.  So without tasting the food, I can only comment on the latte and decor. I would give the atmosphere and decor a ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ but the coffee ⭐️⭐️⭐️ for the taste and price at $4 dollars. Lastly, I was really puzzled when I get the latte, it was half full in my to-go cup, is that the standard nowadays?

My Palestinian friends cite this as the only place to go in Boston for authentic Palestinian food. From the moment you walk in, it feels very cozy. You can sit on couches or tables/chairs on the first floor or head downstairs for more space. Service is friendly though food was a bit slow for our large party. Their chicken tikka is cooked so tenderly and falafel is quite flavorful. The hummus is a must-have for any meal. I also had the mint green smoothie, which was delicious and fresh. For my friend's birthday, we got the knafeh, and it was hot, crispy, and quite sweet. I was so stuffed from the meal and would definitely go again!

I am actually surprised how this place with the  quality I saw got 4 stars so far. I am very easy-going and not picky at all. but I really wonder how people could find any positive points in this place! we have been there for breakfast at a time that the cafe was not crowded, yet it took a very long time until someone showed up to take orders. the glasses were not clean and we showed it to the waiter. we even asked the waiter to get us some disposable paper cups instead. the tray in which coffee and tea was served was so dirty as if it was never cleaned or washed. I have had Turkish coffee many times before and it is not supposed to taste like that. it contained very big grains and i could only drink two sips until i reached the solids. not that i could anyway drink more than that because the cardamom taste in the turkish coffee was so dominant. Even flowers were suffering at this place as they were not watered and flowers had fallen down from the hanging pot. DO NOT GO THERE.

Really, really poor. We sat in the corner, and were greeted by a distinct smell reminiscent of a port-o-potty at the end of Bonnarro. Arabic coffee was poorly made, and my friend's "farmer's omelette" must have been made by a farmer who specializes exclusively in watery, tasteless tomatoes, as that was the primary ingredient. She said it wasn't even warm enough for the cheese to have properly melted, and that the favorite part of her meal was the toast. My omelette was equally bland.  Service was terribly slow and a bit rude. At one point I had to get up to refill my own water since I had given up hope of having a server help, and spent about 15 minutes trying to get a check so that we could leave at the end. Would have gotten better service by strapping a tray to the back of a golden retriever.  Overall, worst $40 I've ever spent on two omelettes.

The plate was not in the menu and he hided the price from us and also pretended that the plate was not that big, which is why we didn't ask the price. He also added couple of other stuff that we didn't order. The bill turned out to be $345!!!  They had also added 20% tip. The price of plate itself was $195 and I think it was enough for 14 people. You think when you order a plate it should become cheaper but here it doubled the price. If we had ordered separately it would become $20 each at most. The food quality was ok but not great.
